@deffn {Function} csign (@var{expr})

Attempts to determine the sign of @var{expr} on the basis of the facts
in the current data base without assuming that @var{expr} is
real-valued. It returns one of the following answers: @code{pos}
(positive), @code{neg} (negative), @code{zero}, @code{pz} (positive or
zero), @code{nz} (negative or zero), @code{pn} (positive or negative),
@code{pnz} (positive, negative, or zero), @code{imaginary}
(purely imaginary), or @code{complex}, (complex, i.e. nothing known).

Note that while this function does not assume that @var{expr} is
real-valued, it still assumes that variables are real-valued unless
declared otherwise. This means that @code{csign(z)} will return
@code{pnz} unless @code{declare(z,complex)} or
@code{declare(z,imaginary)} has been evaluated beforehand.

See also @mrefdot{sign}

